AUDIO: 'Hey guys, if your new HighDream 01 images are coming out with fuzzy details and weird plastic skin, in this video I\'ll show you exactly how to fix it in seconds. So, there is a new model named HighDream 01 image, which is great for text to'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image, image to image, image editing, and storyboards. But, whenever a new model releases, it comes with many, many problems. Right now, people are getting fuzzy'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'results and plastic-looking skin, and they\'re struggling to get better outputs. So, we have the solution for it, and we\'re going to fix that in this video. So, first, let\'s talk about what\'s new'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in this 8-billion parameter model. Other models use a VAE to compress the image, but HighDream 01 is completely different.'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'According to official research, it removes the VAE completely and operates directly on raw image pixels using a single token space. In my first test, the result showed'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plastic skin and colors that popped too much. So, I tried another image, and you can see the skin still looks plastic, and the background is not perfectly black.'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And to fix this, I add one more node, which is model sampling SD3. I place it between these nodes and set the value to three. And why do I use this?'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because HighDream 01 processes raw pixels instead of compressed latents, it mathematically needs a custom noise removal curve that ComfyUI doesn\'t apply by default.'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I added model sampling SD3 and set the value to three, which fixes the skin problem. Now, everything else stays the same, and I just hit run. So, by adding this one node, you can'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'immediately see the difference between these two images. Because the model needs a custom noise removal curve that ComfyUI doesn\'t apply automatically, this node fixes it.'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can see the result is good, but the skin is still not perfect. So, what else can we do to make it better?'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, here I tried changing the settings. First, I set my LoRA strength value to 0.5. Then I changed the sampler to Euler SDE and made the scheduler beta.'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But with the strength at 0.5, the quality drops. Something is missing, so I don\'t think this is the right value. Next, I decided to test a LoRA strength'

[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of 0.2, increased the CFG to two, and increased the steps to 40 just to see what happens. Now, this gives me a better result, but'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the skin is still too smooth. So, let\'s try one more method. We\'ll keep the strength at 0.2, the steps at 40, and the CFG at two. With these exact settings, the standard'

[03:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sampler is not the best choice. So, we switch the sampler back to Euler SDE and keep the beta scheduler. Now, you can see the image looks much better.'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, here is the most important part. With 40 steps and a CFG of two, we can finally use negative prompts. This was the real problem. We were getting bad results earlier'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because I had removed the negative prompt node. And by using a CFG of two and 40 steps along with a negative prompt, the image brings back a lot of details.'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, when we use the CFG of one, those details were removed. If you want maximum detail with the full model, this is the best method to use. Now, we get the result and we know the'

